WEBVTT

00:00.354 --> 00:03.358
Hear God's word from John chapter one.

00:05.881 --> 00:12.268
In the beginning was the word, and the word was with God, and the word was God, and he was in the beginning with God.

00:13.069 --> 00:18.395
All things were made through him, and without him was not anything made that was made.

00:19.577 --> 00:23.101
In him was life, and the life was the light of men.

00:23.161 --> 00:27.506
The light shines in the darkness, and the darkness is not overcome it.

00:28.898 --> 00:31.240
And the word became flesh and dwelt among us.

00:32.461 --> 00:40.069
And we have seen His glory, glorious of the only Son from the Father, full of grace and truth.

00:41.030 --> 00:46.095
The grass withers and the flowers fade, but the word of our God will stand forever.

00:46.355 --> 00:47.276
Amen, you may be seated.

00:49.598 --> 00:55.044
Pray with me, merciful and gracious Father in heaven.

00:56.205 --> 00:57.586
We give you thanks for your word,

00:59.202 --> 01:03.406
Your word which is not far off but is drawn near in the person.

01:04.387 --> 01:07.790
Your word which is life and light.

01:08.331 --> 01:09.752
Your word which brings healing.

01:10.773 --> 01:15.738
I pray that your light and your healing would come to us as we meditate on your word this morning.

01:16.458 --> 01:17.399
It's in your name that we pray.

01:17.459 --> 01:18.500
Amen.

01:24.606 --> 01:28.690
A handful of years ago, there was this great commercial.

01:29.090 --> 01:31.272
That only aired in Europe, you might have seen it.

01:31.312 --> 01:35.216
It's probably made a lot of sermon illustrations because it was so good.

01:35.236 --> 01:48.669
It opens with this guy, this old man in Poland receiving a package and then he gets another package and then you see him sitting on a computer and what he's doing, he's learning to speak English.

01:49.530 --> 01:54.315
And as it goes, he starts putting sticky notes around his house like pot, you know, door, fridge.

01:54.975 --> 01:57.778
The dog gets a sticky note too.

01:58.242 --> 02:05.634
And then fast forward to him getting on a plane and then getting off a plane in downtown London and walking up to a door and he opens the door and it's his son.

02:05.694 --> 02:08.057
He gives a son this hug and then he sees his daughter-in-law.

02:09.960 --> 02:10.521
Quick greeting.

02:10.561 --> 02:17.212
Then he makes his way into the house and gets on his knees and stares at this little girl in the eyes and says, hi, I'm your grandpa.

02:17.432 --> 02:21.118
And it's just touching beautiful moment, beautiful scene.

02:22.340 --> 02:26.386
And I mean, this is a scene, a picture.

02:27.074 --> 02:29.718
of what God does for us in the incarnation.

02:30.559 --> 02:39.912
And God does the same thing for us as he learns our language, as he stoops down, as he comes to meet us where we are, coming to us where we are.

02:39.972 --> 02:50.767
And when you think about the idea of the incarnation, and most of you, I'm guessing walking in this room is something you've thought about before, and maybe you feel like, yeah, I got that down and God came and flashed cool.

02:50.787 --> 02:52.229
Let's move on to the next part of the story.

02:53.471 --> 02:55.794
But it's wild to actually consider

02:56.482 --> 03:04.274
just what it means that the God who made everything, sustains everything, actually took on flesh, flesh and blood.

03:05.396 --> 03:08.481
It's actually a pretty wild thing to consider.

03:08.541 --> 03:18.095
And I'm not sure that our imaginations are actually big enough to really grapple with the reality of what that means.

03:18.156 --> 03:24.946
And I think because it overwhelms our senses and imaginations, we kind of like, yeah, it happened, accept it, we kind of move on.

03:25.122 --> 03:30.331
But this morning, I want us to dwell on this amazing truth.

03:31.173 --> 03:45.218
Because I think oftentimes, we can have a tendency, depending on your perspective and how you grew up and history and all those things, we can have a tendency to pit like the grandness, the bigness of God, against the nearness of God.

03:45.699 --> 03:49.906
What I mean by that is this, like some of us, like you love the idea that God is.

03:50.114 --> 03:55.400
Big, he's this massive being that he almost feels cold, and you don't mind that.

03:55.460 --> 03:56.661
Just like walking into a cathedral.

03:56.701 --> 03:59.144
You feel the grandness of God in those places.

03:59.164 --> 04:01.146
And it's this amazing thing, but it's also a little bit cold.

04:02.128 --> 04:06.933
Some of you prefer that, or we pit that against the idea that he's super near, that he's my buddy.

04:06.953 --> 04:09.075
It's that Jesus is my homeboy, t-shirt kind of guy.

04:09.095 --> 04:11.238
It's a guy that when he prays, he says, oh, Papa Lord.

04:12.159 --> 04:13.440
It's like, oh, I don't know if he should say that.

04:13.480 --> 04:15.102
But I get what they're after, right?

04:15.142 --> 04:18.546
The fact that God is near, he's personal, he's a knowable being.

04:18.658 --> 04:20.941
And sometimes we say, oh, you're either this or you're that.

04:21.001 --> 04:25.606
And I think in the incarnation, you get this profound reality that it's both and.

04:25.626 --> 04:26.227
It's yes.

04:26.968 --> 04:27.609
He is near.

04:29.291 --> 04:31.033
He's near as the person sitting next to you.

04:31.373 --> 04:33.276
He's flesh and bony as the person sitting next to you.

04:33.296 --> 04:36.219
But he's also still God.

04:36.239 --> 04:48.594
And this morning is not going to be a very practical sermon because I just really want us to, for a moment here, marvel at the character of God.

04:50.402 --> 04:54.848
Marvel at the fact that God is the God who draws in the air.

04:55.809 --> 05:04.201
And I think as we marvel at this, it'll encourage and strengthen us to follow him as we draw near to him, to each other, and to those around us in this world.

05:04.762 --> 05:07.485
So we're just gonna ask three very simple questions this morning.

05:08.387 --> 05:09.668
The first is, who is Jesus?

05:10.610 --> 05:13.574
The second question is, how did Jesus come on earth?

05:14.255 --> 05:16.458
And finally, why did Jesus come to earth?

05:16.938 --> 05:19.762
So three simple questions.

05:19.874 --> 05:26.925
These are simple enough to where even if I just said, hey, fill me an answer to each of these questions, you could probably get some of this answer right.

05:27.306 --> 05:28.428
You probably get all the answers right.

05:29.409 --> 05:36.100
And when we jump into topics like incarnation, you're probably not gonna hear anything that's profoundly new to you this morning.

05:37.823 --> 05:39.926
But if we're honest, we always need to be reminded of these truths.

05:39.946 --> 05:44.754
This is why we gather each week to be reminded of these ancient truths because we are forgetful people

05:44.866 --> 05:47.208
and we need to be reminded and encouraged by these truths.

05:47.248 --> 05:48.830
And so I hope that's what happens this morning.

05:48.870 --> 05:51.632
So first question, who is Jesus?

05:51.672 --> 05:52.453
Who is this guy?

05:52.493 --> 05:58.459
The first thing we learn here about Jesus is in the beginning was the word.

05:59.880 --> 06:02.943
So Jesus is, there's two truths about who Jesus is.

06:03.003 --> 06:04.244
The first is that Jesus is the word.

06:04.264 --> 06:06.987
And of course, we know this is Jesus.

06:07.027 --> 06:11.391
The word became flesh and dwelt among us and says in verse 14 and goes on, this is Jesus Christ.

06:11.411 --> 06:14.354
So we know that this is Jesus is the word.

06:15.426 --> 06:19.412
in this word, but what does it mean that he is this word?

06:19.452 --> 06:26.843
Well, first clue that we get to understand what does it mean that he is the word is that it's in the beginning.

06:28.606 --> 06:29.647
So where is this word found?

06:29.667 --> 06:30.949
This word is found in the beginning.

06:31.871 --> 06:42.226
John's story about Jesus doesn't begin with the manger scene, doesn't begin with the angels, it doesn't begin with Joseph and Mary,

06:42.882 --> 06:52.012
His story about who Jesus is, which all the gospels write are stories about who Jesus is, who is this guy, begins in the beginning.

06:52.592 --> 06:56.877
When is the, in the beginning, it's the words from, from Genesis chapter one, in the beginning.

06:59.019 --> 07:02.503
In the beginning, Genesis, this is, this is the word.

07:02.803 --> 07:03.724
This is who Jesus says.

07:03.764 --> 07:07.027
He's the word that was there at the beginning of all time.

07:08.749 --> 07:09.650
And it later says,

07:09.794 --> 07:14.480
You know, later in the Gospel of John, Jesus says the words that before Abraham was, I am.

07:14.961 --> 07:16.483
Jesus taken the very name of God.

07:16.503 --> 07:18.005
He's not a creature among creatures.

07:18.966 --> 07:21.509
He is the word that caused all creation to come forth.

07:21.529 --> 07:31.162
And that's what you see here, that he was in the beginning with God and all things were made through him and without him was not anything made that was made.

07:31.182 --> 07:34.286
A little tongue twister sentence for me anyways.

07:35.287 --> 07:36.248
So this is who Jesus says.

07:36.769 --> 07:37.650
He is the word.

07:38.146 --> 07:40.288
He is the word that wasn't just present at creation.

07:40.328 --> 07:42.451
He is the word that was there doing the creating.

07:43.151 --> 07:46.715
You know, in Psalm 33, it's the word speaks the heavens into existence.

07:46.735 --> 07:48.317
This is what, who Jesus is.

07:48.337 --> 07:51.781
And Psalm 107, his word heals his people.

07:52.021 --> 07:52.662
This is who he is.

07:52.722 --> 07:53.363
He is the word.

07:54.324 --> 08:01.331
He's not just another prophet coming to speak God's word, just with the prophets where the prophets, you know, God gave his word to the prophets to speak his word to the people.

08:01.351 --> 08:03.954
No, Jesus was the word.

08:05.698 --> 08:08.542
which leads to the second thing that this leads to is what is this word?

08:08.562 --> 08:09.904
Well, it's God Himself.

08:10.024 --> 08:15.411
Jesus says, God, it says the word was with God and the word was God.

08:16.993 --> 08:22.461
I mean, this is the foundation to what we believe about the nature of who God is is found in this, the nature of the Trinity.

08:23.803 --> 08:29.691
That Jesus, the both these things are true, that Jesus is both with God and He is God.

08:30.392 --> 08:35.058
He's a distinct person, this is the nature of the Trinity, the Father, Son and the Holy Spirit, they all distinct,

08:35.170 --> 08:38.594
persons, but one nature, one will.

08:39.375 --> 08:41.417
Jesus did not come as an assistant to God.

08:41.477 --> 08:44.060
He came as fully God and fully man.

08:44.661 --> 08:45.402
This is who he is.

08:46.723 --> 09:03.602
The thing to consider about this is this, that the God who always was and always will be the God who out of creation, out of his love created all things, the God who says that he knows all the hairs on your head, the God who causes the sun to rise each day

09:05.058 --> 09:13.246
That transcendent one, the big one who's over all and see all and sovereign over all things, is he has come near, he has made himself knowable.

09:15.188 --> 09:16.970
The word has taken on flesh.

09:18.151 --> 09:19.973
There's knowable as the person sitting next to you.

09:20.013 --> 09:23.216
It's like if you just poke the person next to you for a second.

09:24.217 --> 09:25.398
You know, like they're physical, right?

09:25.438 --> 09:26.760
You can feel him, you can touch him.

09:28.401 --> 09:29.102
This is Jesus.

09:30.263 --> 09:31.184
He lived as an infant.

09:31.504 --> 09:33.266
The word took on flesh.

09:33.442 --> 09:34.724
He became as an infant.

09:34.744 --> 09:36.466
He got scrapes on his knees.

09:36.506 --> 09:37.948
He lost childhood games.

09:38.509 --> 09:39.210
He was hungry.

09:39.751 --> 09:41.833
He mourned the loss of his friend.

09:42.514 --> 09:45.358
He took pity on the crowds that didn't have a shepherd over them.

09:45.378 --> 09:48.603
He knew what it was like to not know where he was going to lay his head.

09:48.623 --> 09:52.909
In those moments, Jesus was never less God.

09:54.371 --> 09:54.991
He is both.

09:56.634 --> 09:57.995
He is always both.

09:59.097 --> 10:02.802
I mean, if he were only human, he could sympathize with us, but he couldn't save us.

10:03.394 --> 10:07.899
There's only divine, he couldn't become the second Adam to lead humanity into a new creation.

10:07.959 --> 10:09.661
He is both and he's always both.

10:11.643 --> 10:12.844
It's a marvel at that truth.

10:14.966 --> 10:15.967
So how does this happen?

10:16.748 --> 10:18.730
How can the eternal take on flesh and do this?

10:19.171 --> 10:20.192
Let's see if there's a second question.

10:20.232 --> 10:22.154
How did Jesus actually come on earth?

10:22.895 --> 10:23.816
How did Jesus come on earth?

10:24.697 --> 10:26.138
There's a second question we're going to turn to.

10:27.520 --> 10:29.842
Speaking about how Jesus accomplishes this task.

10:31.106 --> 10:39.916
He doesn't accomplish this task of coming near us by making us go to him, but through this wild descent from heaven to earth, he draws near to his people.

10:40.657 --> 10:52.310
I mean, Philippians 2 says it like this, that though he was in the form of God, though Jesus, that he there was in the form of God, he emptied himself, taking the form of a servant, both in the light, born in the likeness of men.

10:52.370 --> 10:56.274
And speaking of this descent that Jesus goes into from heaven,

10:56.802 --> 10:58.865
to earth, taken on the likeness of men.

10:58.885 --> 11:02.671
And I think there's two ways we see that he descends into our likeness here.

11:02.711 --> 11:06.958
The first is that the word becomes flesh.

11:09.342 --> 11:11.265
The word became flesh.

11:13.228 --> 11:15.272
It's speaking about the incarnation.

11:16.173 --> 11:24.306
You see us Lewis talks about the incarnation like a diver that's leaving the beautiful sunny shore and the green grass and the

11:24.514 --> 11:32.367
with blue skies and diving into the water and descending into the darkness to grab something of a treasure and bring it back into the light.

11:32.387 --> 11:35.352
This is like a good image for what the incarnation is like.

11:35.412 --> 11:44.046
Jesus leaving the glory of heaven, taking on the form of a servant, the poverty of man, being born to draw near, to go into the darkness.

11:45.749 --> 11:47.311
But the darkness doesn't overcome him.

11:48.093 --> 11:51.378
This is what Jesus does and it gives us an imagination.

11:51.618 --> 11:52.039
for this.

11:52.299 --> 11:56.325
Jesus taking on flesh is Him entering another world, which is our world.

11:58.028 --> 11:59.230
This is what the incarnation is.

11:59.270 --> 12:11.770
And even to get more into this darkness and the reality of the weight of what He's doing, the incarnation comes from the root word of where we get carnal or carnage or carnious out up if you're into that.

12:12.631 --> 12:12.871
I am.

12:13.372 --> 12:14.614
It means in fleshing.

12:15.035 --> 12:17.118
Literally taking flesh on yourself.

12:17.158 --> 12:19.762
This is His descent, taking our flesh

12:20.642 --> 12:21.643
and all that it means.

12:21.663 --> 12:24.826
I think about all that means to have your own flesh.

12:24.846 --> 12:25.907
There's weakness there.

12:25.987 --> 12:31.012
There's frailty, which he will experience fully when he goes to the cross.

12:32.614 --> 12:35.017
His flesh isn't less human than yours or mine.

12:37.119 --> 12:48.370
He doesn't partially come onto the earth into our flesh, but fully enters the darkness of the world by taking our flesh and all that means on himself.

12:48.450 --> 12:54.079
Not only does he come on the earth and the flesh, he descends into our wilderness.

12:56.703 --> 13:00.508
We see this in verse 14 that it says that he dwelt among us.

13:01.430 --> 13:05.416
This word dwelt among, it means tabernacle, which means he makes a home.

13:06.017 --> 13:08.140
This is meant to harken back to Israel's history.

13:09.222 --> 13:11.746
When God tabernacle among his people, when was it?

13:11.766 --> 13:17.234
When they were in the wilderness, when they were wandering out of Egypt to the Promised Land and they set up these tents

13:17.378 --> 13:20.883
was where they lived and God said, I'm set up a tent for me in the middle of you.

13:21.684 --> 13:22.906
And that's gonna be my temple.

13:22.946 --> 13:24.408
You're in a tent, I'm in a dwelling tent.

13:24.428 --> 13:29.134
They didn't build a temple for God, like a home for him until they had homes.

13:29.194 --> 13:31.377
And so he's like, hey, where you are, I'm gonna be.

13:32.018 --> 13:32.839
He dwells with them.

13:33.120 --> 13:35.884
You're in a tent in the wilderness, all being a tent in the wilderness.

13:36.865 --> 13:38.387
God is doing this again in Christ.

13:41.952 --> 13:46.418
Jesus doesn't come in the flesh and live in the nice places and the palaces

13:47.394 --> 13:50.198
where he's got servants attending to him, making sure he's never hungry, no.

13:50.238 --> 13:52.862
It's not what he does.

13:52.962 --> 13:59.832
He lives where we live in our wildernesses, in our weightings, in our wanderings, in our weariness, in our uncertainties.

13:59.852 --> 14:01.434
That's where Jesus dwells with us.

14:03.477 --> 14:10.848
To use another analogy from scripture, he is the God who yokes himself to you, who attaches himself to you.

14:10.888 --> 14:15.154
These and your burdens, not by merely taking them away,

14:16.866 --> 14:20.813
but by taking them on himself, by carrying them with you and for you.

14:21.754 --> 14:28.004
This truth about Jesus' yoke in himself to us, I think it's both an amazing truth, and it's a bit of an unsettling one too.

14:28.425 --> 14:40.685
It's amazing that God would do that, that the God who created all things, sustains the thing, come and serve us and yoke himself to us and carry us, take our problems on himself.

14:40.745 --> 14:43.570
It's an amazing thing to think that God would draw near to do this.

14:44.162 --> 14:49.530
But when you dwell on it a little bit, it can be unsettling because it's like, well, I don't suppose you could like speed this up.

14:50.291 --> 14:55.078
You speed this process up, you know, like it's great that you're drawing near to me, but why not just take these burdens away?

14:55.158 --> 14:56.800
Why leave these burdens on me?

14:57.902 --> 15:01.527
If you have the power to take them away, I'd prefer you just take them away, right?

15:02.148 --> 15:06.975
It's amazing and it's unsettling and reality description doesn't give us a great answer to that question.

15:07.336 --> 15:09.058
At least not one that often satisfies us.

15:09.138 --> 15:10.480
John doesn't really give us an answer.

15:10.520 --> 15:11.762
He just gives us a person.

15:12.578 --> 15:16.543
And that person is God in the flesh who comes and draws near.

15:17.764 --> 15:29.078
There is waiting, waiting for the renewal of all things, waiting to get our inheritance, which is for us in heaven, waiting in the world still infected with sin.

15:29.138 --> 15:31.381
There is waiting, but we don't wait alone.

15:31.802 --> 15:34.785
There is wilderness still, but wilderness with God who is near.

15:37.328 --> 15:42.034
The reality is, depending on how strong and dark your wilderness is, this doesn't always sound like enough.

15:42.146 --> 15:42.687
What is it?

15:43.488 --> 15:45.972
How does that nearness of God actually help us?

15:46.192 --> 15:53.002
How does the incarnation help us when it doesn't take us the darkness necessarily away?

15:54.765 --> 15:55.926
So these are our final questions.

15:55.946 --> 15:57.789
Well, why then did Jesus come at all?

16:00.213 --> 16:01.234
Why did Jesus come at all?

16:01.254 --> 16:11.890
I think the reason we sometimes wonder if Jesus' presence nearness to us helps at all when we're struggling is because we underestimate

16:12.578 --> 16:17.583
Just what it means for the God who made all things and sustained all things to be near to us.

16:18.423 --> 16:19.284
So why did he come?

16:19.384 --> 16:28.433
Well verse 14, we see this, and the word became flesh and dwelt among us, and we have seen his glory, glory as the only son from the Father full of grace and truth.

16:29.674 --> 16:30.695
What does this tell us?

16:32.236 --> 16:33.898
He's come to make himself known to us.

16:35.219 --> 16:37.061
Why that you might see him.

16:38.683 --> 16:42.386
Now this is not speaking about like the image of Christ,

16:43.266 --> 16:45.609
We can't see him, right?

16:47.372 --> 16:56.064
In heaven now, it's not talking about like if a sketch artist was able to perfectly capture who Jesus was and show us that picture so we could see him.

16:56.084 --> 16:58.467
That's not what it's talking about here.

16:58.587 --> 17:03.875
In fact, John's not describing the features of Jesus here, strong jawbone.

17:03.895 --> 17:04.876
That's not what you find here.

17:05.277 --> 17:06.058
How does he describe him?

17:06.158 --> 17:07.660
Seeing his glory.

17:09.983 --> 17:11.986
That's what it's about, his glory.

17:12.898 --> 17:16.343
So what is this glory that he wants us to see in him?

17:17.605 --> 17:26.097
Well, at least an aspect of it is the glory is overflowing light of Christ of God himself.

17:26.198 --> 17:37.394
And I mean, John's gospel kind of gets at this when his whole gospel is building towards the awesome moment of the transfiguration where you get this divine, this radiance, which

17:37.506 --> 17:44.135
echoes kind of what happened in Moses when he went up Mount Sinai and he came down with God and he was glowing, he was radiating.

17:44.495 --> 17:46.137
The glory of God is his radiance.

17:47.819 --> 17:50.643
It's his light, it's his presence.

17:53.467 --> 17:55.469
It's heaven, right?

17:55.529 --> 17:58.193
And where does God, what is heaven?

17:58.213 --> 18:05.202
But it's this place that God lives and it's, his glory fills, his light fills and radiates all over heaven.

18:05.730 --> 18:11.256
Well, in Christ, that radiating glory, that radiating light is coming from heaven to earth.

18:12.197 --> 18:19.064
And this is what he wants us to see is the nearness of his glory, of his presence, of his guiding light.

18:19.144 --> 18:22.327
Heaven itself is making a descent to earth.

18:22.908 --> 18:27.092
And what does that mean for us other than this light, this glory, this radiance?

18:28.193 --> 18:33.138
Well, the rubber meets the road here where we see it's full of grace and truth.

18:34.594 --> 18:36.976
That is what heavenly glory is described as.

18:37.016 --> 18:41.380
It's where God's grace and truth are expansive and everywhere.

18:43.242 --> 18:45.665
The glory of Jesus is His grace and truth.

18:47.386 --> 18:51.210
And what is this grace, the unmerited favor of the Lord?

18:51.290 --> 18:52.491
It's not something you can earn.

18:52.531 --> 18:56.175
It doesn't wait for darkness to retreat before it advances.

18:56.215 --> 19:03.922
It dives down into the darkness and rescues you, bringing what along with it is the truth, which is why Jesus came.

19:04.482 --> 19:06.285
He didn't come to play human.

19:06.865 --> 19:21.386
He didn't come to live a day in the life of, but to make himself known to you that you might know his grace and truth and be delivered from darkness, to make his light known, to make his glory known in you that it might spread over this whole earth.

19:23.168 --> 19:27.474
This is why he has come to make his glory known.

19:29.410 --> 19:34.799
And the place on earth that this glory and this grace and this truth of Jesus shines most clearly is when.

19:36.061 --> 19:38.646
